1 Summary Findings

1.1 Intuitive Grouping & Missing Value Handling

1.1.1 Intuitive Grouping

Summary Table for Intuitive Grouping & Missing Values:

Variable Name Level Primary Category Notes
viewership_(millions) Episode C1 (Profit) Direct audience size measure (No missing value)
imdb_episode_votes_num Episode C1 (Profit) Audience engagement/popularity proxy (0.02% Missing - Very Low)
rt_season_all_audience_score Season C1 (Profit) Broad audience satisfaction measure (10.54% Missing - Moderate)
rt_season_all_audience_num Season C1 (Profit) Audience engagement volume proxy (1.51% Missing - Low)
imdb_episode_rating_score Episode Ambiguous (Leans C1) Audience appreciation, but high scores can align with Prestige (0.02% Missing - Very Low)
imdb_episode_num_award_all Episode C2 (Prestige) Direct peer/industry recognition for episode (No missing value)
imdb_season_num_award_all Season C2 (Prestige) Direct peer/industry recognition for season(No missing value)
imdb_show_num_award_all Show C2 (Prestige) Direct peer/industry recognition for show (strongest) (No missing value)
..._num_narrative/prod/acting_award All C2 (Prestige) Nuance on type of acclaim (No missing value)
rt_season_all_critics_score Season C2 (Prestige) Direct critical acclaim measure (49.92% Missing - Very High)
rt_season_all_critics_num Season C2 (Prestige) Critical attention proxy (correlates with acclaim) (14.23% Missing - Moderate)

1.1.2 Missing Value Pattern

Before deciding on how to handle missing values of reward-related variables, we first wanted to look through their distribution patterns. Here is the summary of their pattern:

  1. Missingness by Simple Genre: missingness in RT data, particularly critic scores (rt_season_all_critics_score ~50% missing), is large and exhibits genre bias. While IMDb data shows near-complete coverage, RT data availability is lower for potentially niche or less mainstream genres (e.g., Westerns) compared to high-volume genres like Sitcoms or Dramas. This suggests platform-specific coverage limitations may systematically underrepresent certain content types in RT-based analyses.
  2. Missingness by Network (Top 10): a clear pattern emerges for rt_season_all_critics_score: Major broadcast networks (abc, cbs, fox, nbc) show significantly higher missingness (brighter yellow) compared to major cable/premium networks (amc, fx, hbo, showtime), which are darker (less missing). A similar, though less extreme, pattern might be visible for the other RT variables. IMDb variables show low missingness across networks.
  3. Missingness by Time Period:a very clear temporal trend exists for all RT variables. Missingness is extremely high (bright yellow) in the earliest time periods (pre-2000s) and steadily decreases (darker colors) until the mid-to-late 2010s, where it’s lowest. There might be a slight uptick in missingness again in the most recent period (2022-2023). IMDb variables show consistently low missingness across all time periods.

Note: Considering IMDb launched in 1990 and RT in 1998, A relevant PNAS paper /(Y. Lin, S. Yang, W. Han,& J.G. Lu, 2023)/ handled this by starting their sample in 1998 to avoid bias issues with evaluating movies that had reputations before these review sites were common. Their reasoning: “To preclude the concern about the audience’s potential biases when evaluating movies with established reputations, we focus on the period after the launch of these review sites (55). Our sample period therefore starts in 1998 (i.e., the year RT was launched) and ends in 2021.”

1.1.3 Missing Value Handling Plan Table

Variable Name # Missing % Missing Primary Issue(s) Handling Plan Rationale
rt_season_all_critics_score 12655 49.92% Very High Missingness; Systematic Temporal/Network Bias Exclude Column from primary C1/C2 feature engineering & core analyses. Optionally use in subgroup analyses on available data only. Consider a Missingness Indicator. Too much missing data for reliable imputation or listwise deletion without massive data loss/bias. The systematic nature makes it hard to use representatively.
rt_season_all_critics_num 3608 14.23% Moderate Missingness; Systematic Bias Option 1 (Simpler): Listwise Deletion for specific analyses requiring it. Option 2 (Advanced): Multiple Imputation (MICE) if needed for modeling. Add Missingness Indicator. Moderate missingness still risks bias with deletion. MICE preserves sample size but adds complexity/assumptions. Indicator captures potential systematic effects.
rt_season_all_audience_score 2671 10.54% Moderate Missingness; Systematic Bias Option 1 (Simpler): Listwise Deletion for specific analyses requiring it. Option 2 (Advanced): Multiple Imputation (MICE). Add Missingness Indicator. Similar rationale to rt_critics_num. Less missing than critics score, making it slightly more viable.
rt_season_all_audience_num 383 1.51% Low Missingness; Needs Numeric Conversion Listwise Deletion (Remove rows). Convert to numeric estimate (e.g., midpoint logic) before deletion. Missingness is low enough that removing the affected rows has minimal impact on sample size or bias. Numeric conversion is needed for analysis.
imdb_episode_rating_score 6 0.02% Very Low Missingness Listwise Deletion (Remove rows). Negligible amount of missing data; removing rows is simplest and won’t affect results.
imdb_episode_votes_num 6 0.02% Very Low Missingness; Needs ‘K’ Conversion Listwise Deletion (Remove rows). Convert ‘K’/‘M’ notation to numeric before deletion. Negligible amount of missing data; removing rows is simplest. Conversion needed for analysis.

Note: I decide to apply the following simpler plan for handling missing valuesfor the current EDA:(i)Exclude Columns: Remove rt_season_all_critics_score, rt_season_all_critics_num, rt_season_all_audience_score due to high or moderate systematic missingness; (ii) Create Missingness Indicators: Create binary flags (TRUE/FALSE) for the removed columns to potentially use this information later; (iii) Listwise Deletion (Row Removal): Remove rows with missing values in the remaining core reward variables (imdb_episode_rating_score, imdb_episode_votes_num, and the cleaned rt_season_all_audience_num_numeric) as they have very low missingness post-cleaning.

1.5 For Feature Engineering (C1 vs. C2)

C1 (Commercial Popularity) C2 (Critical Acclaim)
High viewership ( Top 25 %) High rating score
High number of votes Presence of awards
Audience-driven success Recognition-driven success

1.5.1 Potential Engineered Features:

  • votes_per_million_viewers = imdb_episode_votes_num / viewership_(millions)
  • award_indicator = if_else(imdb_episode_num_award_all > 0, 1, 0)
  • rating_votes_ratio = imdb_episode_rating_score / log1p(imdb_episode_votes_num)

Note: - Profit (C1) = Big audiences and vote counts, but not necessarily high quality. - Prestige (C2) = Solid ratings and rare awards. - Handle skewness carefully when constructing features (e.g., log-transformation or robust thresholds).

1.6 Genre Reward-Related Patterns

1.6.1 Episode-level Analysis

Genre Pattern Key Features Feature Behavior Interpretation
Highest Viewership per Episode Family Sitcom, Variety, Sitcom, Science Fiction, Medical Drama, Adventure Drama, Police Procedural Very high mean viewership (>11M per episode); CV varies from very low (Family Sitcom 0.14) to moderate (Sitcom 0.60, Medical Drama 0.69). These genres consistently draw large audiences for individual episodes. Family Sitcoms are exceptionally consistent episode-to-episode, while others like Medical Drama and Sitcom show more variability, perhaps due to special event episodes or dips in specific arcs.
Lowest Viewership per Episode Psych. Drama, Comedy Horror, Docu-reality, Teen Drama, Talk Show, Cringe Comedy, Black Comedy Very low mean viewership (<1M per episode); CV often moderate to high (e.g., Cringe Comedy 0.82, Black Comedy 0.65). Individual episodes in these genres typically target smaller, niche audiences. The variability suggests fluctuating interest even within these smaller audiences episode-to-episode.
Highest Rated Episodes (User) Psych. Horror, Docu-reality, Teen Drama, Cringe Comedy, Adventure, Talk Show, Anthology, Historical Drama, Period Drama Very high mean IMDb rating (>8.3); Consistently low CV for ratings (0.04-0.08). Viewers perceive episodes within these genres as consistently high quality (on IMDb). The low CV indicates strong agreement among viewers on the quality of typical episodes.
Most Discussed Episodes (Votes) Horror, Anthology, Teen Drama, Psych. Horror, Adventure, Mockumentary High mean IMDb votes per episode (>5000); CV varies from low (Teen Drama 0.22) to high (Anthology 0.75). Episodes in these genres generate significant online discussion/voting. Some (Teen Drama) show consistent engagement per episode, while others (Anthology, Horror) have more variability, suggesting certain episodes spark much more reaction than others.
Highly Variable Engagement Action, Crime Drama, Animated Sitcom, Sitcom, Drama, Medical Drama, Black Comedy, Comedy-Drama Moderate-to-high mean votes but very high CV (>1.0) and often high positive skew. While these genres can attract votes, the engagement is highly uneven. A few standout/viral episodes likely dominate the voting, pulling up the mean significantly compared to the typical episode (indicated by high CV and skew).
Consistently Low Engagement Variety, Reality Comp, Family Sitcom, Talk Show, Action Drama, Supernatural Drama, Sketch Comedy Very low mean IMDb votes per episode (<300); Often low-to-moderate CV. Individual episodes in these genres typically generate very little online voting/discussion on IMDb, and this pattern is relatively consistent across episodes.
Rare Episode-Level Awards Nearly All Genres Extremely low mean awards per episode (<0.1 for most, often near 0); Very high CV where mean > 0; Many genres show 0 mean for Acting awards. Winning an award for a single specific episode is a very rare event across almost all genres represented here. It’s not a typical measure of success at the episode level. Acting awards for specific episodes seem particularly uncommon in this dataset.
Unawarded Episodes (in data) Neo-Western, Political Thriller, Procedural Drama, Action Fiction, Family Sitcom, Sketch Comedy, etc. Mean imdb_episode_num_award_all is 0. Based on this dataset, individual episodes within these genres received no tracked IMDb awards.
High Viewership Consistency Family Sitcom, Adventure Drama, Mystery, Neo-Western, Supernatural Drama, Historical Drama Low CV for viewership (<0.25). These genres demonstrate relatively stable viewership numbers from one episode to the next.
High Rating Consistency Nearly All Genres Very low CV for imdb_episode_rating_score (mostly <0.10). Regardless of average rating, viewers tend to rate episodes within a given genre similarly, indicating consistent perceived quality episode-to-episode relative to the genre’s average.

1.6.2 Season-level Analysis

Genre Pattern Key Features Feature Behavior Interpretation
High-Viewership Genres Family sitcom, Variety, Sitcom, Adventure drama, Medical drama, Sci-Fi Very high mean viewership (11M–22M+); CV varies from very low (Family Sitcom 0.11) to moderate (Medical Drama 0.73). These genres generally achieve broad audience reach. Some (Family Sitcom, Adventure Drama) are very consistent, while others (Sitcom, Medical Drama) have more variability, likely due to a mix of huge hits and less successful shows within the genre.
Niche/Low-Viewership Genres Psych. drama, Comedy horror, Docu-reality, Teen drama, Black comedy, Talk Very low mean viewership (<1M). Low absolute viewership suggests targeting smaller, specific audiences or less mainstream appeal based on the shows in this dataset.
Consistently High-Rated Psych. horror, Docu-reality, Adventure, Teen drama, Anthology, Neo-Western High mean IMDb rating (>8.3); very low CV for ratings (0.01-0.07). These genres are perceived as consistently high quality by IMDb voters, regardless of viewership levels. The low CV indicates agreement across different seasons/shows within the genre. (Note: some based on low n_obs like Psych. Horror, Teen Drama).
Critically Acclaimed (Awards) Mockumentary, Adventure, Period drama, Anthology, Horror, Political Satire High mean number of total IMDb awards (>20); CV varies. Genres frequently recognized by award bodies. Consistency varies; Period drama (CV=0.17) and Anthology (CV=0.05) are consistently awarded, while Mockumentary (CV=0.87) shows more variance. (Note: Some high means based on low n_obs/zero std e.g., Horror, Pol. Satire).
High & Variable Engagement Action, Crime drama, Horror, Mockumentary, Anthology, Sci-Fi High mean IMDb votes (sum or mean per season); often very high CV (>1.0) and positive skew for votes. Genres containing breakout hits that generate massive online voting/discussion. The high CV and skew show that engagement is dominated by a few extremely popular shows within the genre, alongside many less-voted ones.
Highly Consistent Performers Family sitcom, Adventure drama, Period drama, Neo-Western, Political Satire Low CV (<0.35) across multiple key metrics like viewership, ratings, sometimes votes. These genres exhibit relatively predictable performance levels (popularity, quality perception) across different seasons or shows included in the dataset.
Variable Performers (Sitcoms) Sitcom, Animated sitcom High viewership potential but moderate-to-high CV for viewership (0.65, 1.03) and votes (1.22, 1.08). Sitcoms have huge reach potential (high max viewership/votes) but performance is inconsistent; many shows/seasons don’t reach the heights of the biggest hits, leading to high variability.
Often Missing RT Critic Scores Action drama, Action-adventure, Period sitcom, Police procedural, Reality Comp. High mean for rt_season_all_critics_score_missing (>0.75). Suggests lower critical coverage or focus on Rotten Tomatoes for shows/seasons in these genres compared to others like Drama or Comedy-Drama.
Typically Unawarded Genres Action fiction, Sketch comedy, Talk show Mean imdb_season_num_award_all is 0. Based on the data, these genres (or the specific shows representing them here) consistently receive no awards tracked by IMDb. This might be due to format or specific show selection.

1.7 Time Reward-Related Patterns

1.7.1 Episode-level Analysis

Episode-Level Time Series Analysis

Time Period Key Features (Episode Level) Feature Behavior (Episode Level) Interpretation (Episode Level)
1964-1965 Low N (25 episodes) Moderate viewership (~9M), consistent (CV 0.23). Stable ratings (~7.4). Very low, consistent votes (~188, CV 0.12). No awards. only a single season/show
1988-1989 High, Consistent Viewership Very high mean viewership (~28M), consistent (CV 0.28). Stable ratings (~7.6). Low votes (~307) but very high variability/skew (CV 1.21, Skew 12). Minimal awards. Peak mass viewership era. Episode ratings consistent. IMDb votes show early signs of high variability, suggesting some episodes/shows generated disproportionately more (though still low) engagement. Awards rare at episode level.
1990-1991 Sustained High Viewership High viewership (~23M), consistent (CV 0.26). Stable ratings (~7.5). Votes double (~647), remain extremely variable/skewed (CV 2.13). Minimal awards. Viewership remains high and consistent. Online votes grows but is highly concentrated in specific episodes/shows.
1992-1993 High Viewership Era Continues High viewership (~21M), consistent (CV 0.30). Stable ratings (~7.5). Votes similar (~638), extremely variable/skewed (CV 2.10). Minimal awards. Stable period. High vote variability persists.
1994-1995 High Viewership, Growing Votes High viewership (~20M), consistent (CV 0.34). Stable ratings (~7.7). Votes increase significantly (~1049), very variable/skewed (CV 1.77). Minimal awards. Viewership strong. Notable jump in average episode votes, still highly concentrated.
1996-1997 Viewership Declining, Peak Episode? Lower viewership (~17.5M), more variable (CV 0.42). Stable ratings (~7.7). Votes stable (~1097), very variable/skewed (CV 1.59). Minimal awards. Peak viewership episode (52.9M). Average viewership declines. Presence of a massive outlier episode (likely a series finale like Seinfeld) skews max viewership. Vote variability remains high.
1998-1999 Continued Viewership Decline Lower viewership (~15M), variable (CV 0.43). Stable ratings (~7.7). Votes stable (~1109), very variable/skewed (CV 1.57). Minimal awards. Peak viewership episode (58.5M). Viewership trend continues down. Another huge outlier episode. Vote patterns similar.
2000-2001 Viewership Stabilizing Lower Viewership ~13.4M (CV 0.47). Stable ratings (~7.8). Votes increase (~1314), very variable/skewed (CV 1.40). Minimal awards. Viewership lower but stable. Gradual increase in average episode votes, still highly variable.
2002-2003 Stable Period Viewership ~12.6M (CV 0.52). Stable ratings (~7.85). Votes stable (~1246), variable/skewed (CV 1.21). Minimal awards. Relative stability in viewership and engagement patterns.
2004-2005 Stability, Growing Vote Variability Viewership ~12.7M (CV 0.52). Stable ratings (~7.9). Votes increase (~1416), variable/skewed (CV 1.41). Minimal awards. Peak viewership episode (52.5M). Stable viewership, another huge outlier episode. Average votes creep up, variability high.
2006-2007 Viewership Declines, Votes Increase Lower viewership (~11.4M), variable (CV 0.49). Stable ratings (~7.9). Votes increase (~1576), variable/skewed (CV 1.35). Minimal awards. Viewership drops. Average episode votes continue to rise, variability high.
2008-2009 Online Engagement Surge (Episode Level) Lower viewership (~9.3M), variable (CV 0.51). Stable ratings (~7.9). Votes surge (~1979), variability increases (CV 1.98), max vote high (50k). Minimal awards. Viewership declines. Significant jump in average episode votes and max votes, with increased variability. Clear sign of specific episodes driving much higher online discussion.
2010-2011 Engagement Intensifies Lower viewership (~8.1M), variable (CV 0.60). Stable ratings (~7.9). Votes surge again (~2490), variability high (CV 2.15), max vote higher (83k). Minimal awards. Fragmentation continues. Average and peak episode engagement (votes) continue to climb rapidly. Buzz is concentrating.
2012-2013 Peak Average Episode Votes / Mega-Episodes Lower viewership (~7.2M), variable (CV 0.65). Stable ratings (~7.9). Votes peak on average (~2901), extreme variability (CV 2.93!), max vote explodes (239k). Minimal awards. Highest average episode votes. Extreme variability and max value indicate the era of “mega-episodes” (likely from mega-hit shows like Breaking Bad, Game of Thrones finales/key episodes) dominating online discussion unlike anything before.
2014-2015 Sustained High, Variable Engagement Lower viewership (~6.6M), variable (CV 0.69). High ratings (~8.0). Votes slightly lower (~2722), extreme variability (CV 2.24), high max (114k). Minimal awards. Viewership lower. Engagement remains very high and concentrated in specific high-buzz episodes.
2016-2017 Peak Episode Vote Variability? Lower viewership (~6.0M), variable (CV 0.64). Stable ratings (~7.8). Votes lower (~2375), highest vote variability? (CV 3.69!), high max (236k). Minimal awards. Viewership lower. Variability in episode votes reaches extreme levels, suggesting the gap between highly-discussed episodes and average ones is massive.
2018-2019 Peak Max Episode Votes / GoT Effect? Lower viewership (~5.3M), variable (CV 0.62). Stable ratings (~7.8). Votes lower (~2070), extreme variability (CV 5.43!), highest max vote (270k). Minimal awards. Viewership lower. Highest maximum episode vote count observed (likely Game of Thrones finale effect). Variability remains incredibly high.
2020-2021 Post-Peak Engagement, Lower Viewership Lower viewership (~4.4M), variable (CV 0.59). Stable ratings (~7.7). Votes significantly lower (~1249), variability high (CV 2.04). Minimal awards. Viewership continues decline. Sharp drop in average episode votes from the peak years, though variability remains high. Possible COVID/streaming shifts?
2022-2023 Lowest Viewership, Variable Engagement Lowest viewership (~3.9M), variable (CV 0.58). Stable ratings (~7.7). Votes slightly higher (~1466), variability very high (CV 2.90). Minimal awards. fragmentation Engagement high but variable, driven by specific episodes.
2024-2025 Recent/Ongoing Data (Very Low N) Moderate viewership (~5.0M), consistent (CV 0.40). Stable ratings (~7.7). Votes low (~776), variable (CV 1.87). No awards. Interpret with extreme caution (n=28). Viewership seems okay, but votes are low compared to the past 15 years.

1.7.2 Season-level Analysis

Time Period Key Features Feature Behavior Interpretation
1964-1965 Single observation High viewership (~9M), moderate rating (~7.4). No awards recorded. RT critic score missing. Insufficient data (n=1) to draw conclusions about the period. Represents a single data point.
1988-1989 High & Consistent Viewership Very high mean viewership (~27M) with low CV (0.26). Moderate ratings (~7.5). Low mean votes but very high CV (2.15) & skew. High RT missing. Era characterized by massive, relatively uniform audience reach (broadcast dominance?). Online engagement (votes) was nascent and highly variable/skewed if present. Limited critical tracking on RT.
1990-1991 Sustained High Viewership Viewership still very high (~22M) and very consistent (CV 0.22). Ratings stable. Votes low but highly variable (CV ~2). High RT missing. Continued period of high, consistent mass viewership. Online engagement remains low and variable.
1992-1993 Peak Viewership Era Continues Viewership high (~20M), consistent (CV 0.31). Ratings stable. Votes low, highly variable (CV ~2). High RT missing. Stable period maintaining high viewership levels typical of the era.
1994-1995 High Viewership, Early Signs of Vote Increase? Viewership high (~19.6M), consistent (CV 0.33). Ratings stable. Mean votes slightly higher but still very variable (CV ~1.8). High RT missing. Viewership remains strong. Online engagement might be slightly increasing but is still dominated by a few shows (high CV).
1996-1997 Viewership Declining, More Variable Mean viewership lower (~16M), more variable (CV 0.45). Ratings stable. Votes variable (CV ~1.5). High RT missing. Start of a decline from peak viewership levels, with increasing variability between shows.
1998-1999 Continued Viewership Decline Mean viewership lower (~13.6M), variable (CV 0.45). Ratings stable. Votes variable (CV ~1.4-1.5). High RT missing. Trend of declining average viewership continues.
2000-2001 Viewership Stabilizing Lower Mean viewership ~12.7M (CV 0.49). Ratings stable. Votes variable (CV ~1.2-1.4). High RT missing. Viewership appears to stabilize at a lower level than the early 90s peak.
2002-2003 Stable Viewership & Ratings Mean viewership ~11.7M (CV 0.56). Ratings stable (~7.9). Votes variable (CV ~1.0-1.2). High RT missing. A period of relative stability in viewership and perceived quality, though viewership is more variable than in the past.
2004-2005 Stability, RT Coverage Improving Mean viewership ~11.5M (CV 0.58). Ratings stable. Votes variable (CV ~1.3). RT missing scores decreasing slightly. Continued stability. The decrease in missing RT scores suggests better tracking/more online presence of critical reviews.
2006-2007 Further Viewership Decline Mean viewership drops below 10M (~9.8M), CV 0.53. Ratings stable. Votes variable (CV ~1.3). RT missing decreasing. Significant drop in average viewership.
2008-2009 Rise of Online Engagement Viewership lower (~8.2M), CV 0.58. Ratings stable. Sharp increase in mean IMDb votes (sum/mean), very high CV (1.5-2.1) & skew. RT missing low. Viewership continues decline. Crucially, online engagement (votes) dramatically increases on average, but is highly variable/skewed, indicating the emergence of specific shows driving massive online discussion.
2010-2011 Sustained High, Variable Engagement Viewership lower (~7M), CV 0.67. Ratings stable. Votes remain high, very variable (CV 1.6-2.1) & skewed. RT missing low (audience complete). Fragmentation continues (lower viewership, higher CV). High online engagement persists, dominated by breakout hits. Full audience score coverage on RT.
2012-2013 Peak Engagement Variability / Mega-Hits Viewership lower (~6M), CV 0.75. Ratings stable. Votes extremely high (max values), extremely variable (CV 2.1-2.4) & skewed. RT missing low. Further audience fragmentation. This period shows peak variability and maximums for IMDb votes, suggesting the presence of mega-hit shows generating unprecedented online engagement alongside many less-discussed shows.
2014-2015 Fragmentation & High Engagement Hits Continue Viewership lower (~5.5M), CV 0.77. Ratings stable. Votes high, very variable (CV 1.8-2.2) & skewed. RT missing low. Similar dynamics to 2012-13: lower average viewership but continued potential for high-engagement hits.
2016-2017 Peak Engagement Skewness? Viewership lower (~4.9M), CV 0.76. Ratings stable. Votes high, extremely variable (CV 2.3-3.0!), very skewed, high max. RT missing low. Fragmentation deepens. Vote variability and skewness suggest engagement is increasingly concentrated in massive hits.
2018-2019 Highest Vote Variability & Max / Mega-Hits Era Viewership lower (~4.5M), CV 0.71. Ratings stable. Votes high, highest observed variability (CV 3.2-5.1!) & skew, highest max votes. RT missing low. Peak era for mega-hits driving extreme online engagement. The average show’s viewership continues to decline, but the potential for a single show to dominate online discussion (votes) appears highest here.
2020-2021 Post-Peak Engagement? Lower Viewership Viewership lower (~3.8M), CV 0.66. Ratings stable. Votes lower than peak but still high variability (CV 1.7-1.9). RT critic missing increases. Viewership continues decline. Online engagement (votes) seems slightly down from the absolute peak but remains high and variable. Potential COVID-19 impacts? Increase in missing RT critic scores is notable.
2022-2023 Lowest Viewership, High Variability Lowest mean viewership (~2.9M), very variable (CV 0.84). Ratings stable. Votes high variability (CV 2.1-2.3). RT critic missing high. Lowest average viewership suggests niche audiences, but high variability indicates some shows still achieve moderate success. Engagement remains high but variable. Lower RT critic tracking persists.
2024-2025 Recent/Ongoing Data (Limited n) Moderate viewership (~5.5M), very consistent (CV 0.28). Ratings stable. Votes surprisingly low & less variable (CV ~0.6). Awards highly variable. RT missing high. Interpret with caution (n=12)

2 Reward-related Variable EDA

This section explores the distributions of key reward metrics.

2.1 Missing Value Pattern

Before deciding on how to handle missing values of reward-related variables, we first wanted to look through their distribution patterns. Here is the summary of their pattern:

  1. Missingness by Simple Genre: missingness in RT data, particularly critic scores (rt_season_all_critics_score ~50% missing), is large and exhibits genre bias. While IMDb data shows near-complete coverage, RT data availability is lower for potentially niche or less mainstream genres (e.g., Westerns) compared to high-volume genres like Sitcoms or Dramas. This suggests platform-specific coverage limitations may systematically underrepresent certain content types in RT-based analyses.
  2. Missingness by Network (Top 10): a clear pattern emerges for rt_season_all_critics_score: Major broadcast networks (abc, cbs, fox, nbc) show significantly higher missingness (brighter yellow) compared to major cable/premium networks (amc, fx, hbo, showtime), which are darker (less missing). A similar, though less extreme, pattern might be visible for the other RT variables. IMDb variables show low missingness across networks.
  3. Missingness by Time Period:a very clear temporal trend exists for all RT variables. Missingness is extremely high (bright yellow) in the earliest time periods (pre-2000s) and steadily decreases (darker colors) until the mid-to-late 2010s, where it’s lowest. There might be a slight uptick in missingness again in the most recent period (2022-2023). IMDb variables show consistently low missingness across all time periods.

Note: Considering IMDb launched in 1990 and RT in 1998, A relevant PNAS paper /(Y. Lin, S. Yang, W. Han,& J.G. Lu, 2023)/ handled this by starting their sample in 1998 to avoid bias issues with evaluating movies that had reputations before these review sites were common. Their reasoning: “To preclude the concern about the audience’s potential biases when evaluating movies with established reputations, we focus on the period after the launch of these review sites (55). Our sample period therefore starts in 1998 (i.e., the year RT was launched) and ends in 2021.”

2.1.0.3 Missingness by Group

We examine if missingness in key reward variables is associated with genre, network, or time period.

Findings:

  1. Missingness by Simple Genre:the rt_season_all_critics_score row is predominantly yellow/light green across most genres, indicating high missingness is widespread. Some genres might show slightly darker shades (less missing), possibly mainstream ones like Sitcom or Drama, while others like Western appear very yellow (very high missing %). rt_season_all_audience_score and rt_critics_num show less intense yellow but still variations across genres. IMDb variables remain dark (low missingness).

  2. Missingness by Network (Top 10): a clear pattern emerges for rt_season_all_critics_score: Major broadcast networks (abc, cbs, fox, nbc) show significantly higher missingness (brighter yellow) compared to major cable/premium networks (amc, fx, hbo, showtime), which are darker (less missing). A similar, though less extreme, pattern might be visible for the other RT variables. IMDb variables show low missingness across networks.

  3. Missingness by Time Period:a very clear temporal trend exists for all RT variables. Missingness is extremely high (bright yellow) in the earliest time periods (pre-2000s) and steadily decreases (darker colors) until the mid-to-late 2010s, where it’s lowest. There might be a slight uptick in missingness again in the most recent period (2022-2023). IMDb variables show consistently low missingness across all time periods.

2.1.0.4 Relationship Between Missingness and Other Variables (Viewership & Year)

Creating missingness indicator variables for: rt_season_all_critics_score, rt_season_all_critics_num, rt_season_all_audience_score

Interpretation: Episodes belonging to seasons that are missing an RT critic score tend to have higher viewership on average than episodes belonging to seasons where the critic score is present. (?)

Handle missing value

I decide to apply the following simpler plan for handling missing valuesfor the current EDA:(i)Exclude Columns: Remove rt_season_all_critics_score, rt_season_all_critics_num, rt_season_all_audience_score due to high or moderate systematic missingness; (ii) Create Missingness Indicators: Create binary flags (TRUE/FALSE) for the removed columns to potentially use this information later; (iii) Listwise Deletion (Row Removal): Remove rows with missing values in the remaining core reward variables (imdb_episode_rating_score, imdb_episode_votes_num, and the cleaned rt_season_all_audience_num_numeric) as they have very low missingness post-cleaning.

Analysis of TV Show Statistics by 2-Year Period

Time Period Key Features Feature Behavior Interpretation
1964-1965 Single observation High viewership (~9M), moderate rating (~7.4). No awards recorded. RT critic score missing. Insufficient data (n=1) to draw conclusions about the period. Represents a single data point.
1988-1989 High & Consistent Viewership Very high mean viewership (~27M) with low CV (0.26). Moderate ratings (~7.5). Low mean votes but very high CV (2.15) & skew. High RT missing. Era characterized by massive, relatively uniform audience reach (broadcast dominance?). Online engagement (votes) was nascent and highly variable/skewed if present. Limited critical tracking on RT.
1990-1991 Sustained High Viewership Viewership still very high (~22M) and very consistent (CV 0.22). Ratings stable. Votes low but highly variable (CV ~2). High RT missing. Continued period of high, consistent mass viewership. Online engagement remains low and variable.
1992-1993 Peak Viewership Era Continues Viewership high (~20M), consistent (CV 0.31). Ratings stable. Votes low, highly variable (CV ~2). High RT missing. Stable period maintaining high viewership levels typical of the era.
1994-1995 High Viewership, Early Signs of Vote Increase? Viewership high (~19.6M), consistent (CV 0.33). Ratings stable. Mean votes slightly higher but still very variable (CV ~1.8). High RT missing. Viewership remains strong. Online engagement might be slightly increasing but is still dominated by a few shows (high CV).
1996-1997 Viewership Declining, More Variable Mean viewership lower (~16M), more variable (CV 0.45). Ratings stable. Votes variable (CV ~1.5). High RT missing. Start of a decline from peak viewership levels, with increasing variability between shows.
1998-1999 Continued Viewership Decline Mean viewership lower (~13.6M), variable (CV 0.45). Ratings stable. Votes variable (CV ~1.4-1.5). High RT missing. Trend of declining average viewership continues.
2000-2001 Viewership Stabilizing Lower Mean viewership ~12.7M (CV 0.49). Ratings stable. Votes variable (CV ~1.2-1.4). High RT missing. Viewership appears to stabilize at a lower level than the early 90s peak.
2002-2003 Stable Viewership & Ratings Mean viewership ~11.7M (CV 0.56). Ratings stable (~7.9). Votes variable (CV ~1.0-1.2). High RT missing. A period of relative stability in viewership and perceived quality, though viewership is more variable than in the past.
2004-2005 Stability, RT Coverage Improving Mean viewership ~11.5M (CV 0.58). Ratings stable. Votes variable (CV ~1.3). RT missing scores decreasing slightly. Continued stability. The decrease in missing RT scores suggests better tracking/more online presence of critical reviews.
2006-2007 Further Viewership Decline Mean viewership drops below 10M (~9.8M), CV 0.53. Ratings stable. Votes variable (CV ~1.3). RT missing decreasing. Significant drop in average viewership.
2008-2009 Rise of Online Engagement Viewership lower (~8.2M), CV 0.58. Ratings stable. Sharp increase in mean IMDb votes (sum/mean), very high CV (1.5-2.1) & skew. RT missing low. Viewership continues decline. Crucially, online engagement (votes) dramatically increases on average, but is highly variable/skewed, indicating the emergence of specific shows driving massive online discussion.
2010-2011 Sustained High, Variable Engagement Viewership lower (~7M), CV 0.67. Ratings stable. Votes remain high, very variable (CV 1.6-2.1) & skewed. RT missing low (audience complete). Fragmentation continues (lower viewership, higher CV). High online engagement persists, dominated by breakout hits. Full audience score coverage on RT.
2012-2013 Peak Engagement Variability / Mega-Hits Viewership lower (~6M), CV 0.75. Ratings stable. Votes extremely high (max values), extremely variable (CV 2.1-2.4) & skewed. RT missing low. Further audience fragmentation. This period shows peak variability and maximums for IMDb votes, suggesting the presence of mega-hit shows generating unprecedented online engagement alongside many less-discussed shows.
2014-2015 Fragmentation & High Engagement Hits Continue Viewership lower (~5.5M), CV 0.77. Ratings stable. Votes high, very variable (CV 1.8-2.2) & skewed. RT missing low. Similar dynamics to 2012-13: lower average viewership but continued potential for high-engagement hits.
2016-2017 Peak Engagement Skewness? Viewership lower (~4.9M), CV 0.76. Ratings stable. Votes high, extremely variable (CV 2.3-3.0!), very skewed, high max. RT missing low. Fragmentation deepens. Vote variability and skewness suggest engagement is increasingly concentrated in massive hits.
2018-2019 Highest Vote Variability & Max / Mega-Hits Era Viewership lower (~4.5M), CV 0.71. Ratings stable. Votes high, highest observed variability (CV 3.2-5.1!) & skew, highest max votes. RT missing low. Peak era for mega-hits driving extreme online engagement. The average show’s viewership continues to decline, but the potential for a single show to dominate online discussion (votes) appears highest here.
2020-2021 Post-Peak Engagement? Lower Viewership Viewership lower (~3.8M), CV 0.66. Ratings stable. Votes lower than peak but still high variability (CV 1.7-1.9). RT critic missing increases. Viewership continues decline. Online engagement (votes) seems slightly down from the absolute peak but remains high and variable. Potential COVID-19 impacts? Increase in missing RT critic scores is notable.
2022-2023 Lowest Viewership, High Variability Lowest mean viewership (~2.9M), very variable (CV 0.84). Ratings stable. Votes high variability (CV 2.1-2.3). RT critic missing high. Lowest average viewership suggests niche audiences, but high variability indicates some shows still achieve moderate success. Engagement remains high but variable. Lower RT critic tracking persists.
2024-2025 Recent/Ongoing Data (Limited n) Moderate viewership (~5.5M), very consistent (CV 0.28). Ratings stable. Votes surprisingly low & less variable (CV ~0.6). Awards highly variable. RT missing high. Interpret with caution (n=12)
